## Bug 2: Crawler Appeared to Hang

After resolving the environment-variable issue, the crawler was executed again.

The terminal showed no output and appeared to remain in a running state.

There was no exact crash message because the program had no runtime logging.

The possible blocking locations included:

```text
Crawler construction
        |
        v
Fetcher network request
        |
        v
Framework detection
        |
        v
RenderEngine / CDP connection
        |
        v
PageStorage database operation
        |
        v
HTML parsing
```

The main problem was not immediately knowing whether the crawler was actually hanging or simply performing a long-running operation.

### Debugging Approach

Logging was needed around important execution stages:

```cpp
std::cout << "Before crawler object\n";

Crawler crawler(2);

std::cout << "Before crawl\n";

crawler.crawl("https://example.com");

std::cout << "After crawl\n";
```

More detailed logs can later be added inside `crawl()`:

```cpp
std::cout << "Fetching: " << currentNode.url << "\n";
```

and:

```cpp
std::cout << "Page stored successfully\n";
```

This makes it possible to identify the exact component where execution stops.

